:AZU1_Gene :Synonyms """Azurocidin 1 (Cationic Antimicrobial Protein 37) Gene
AZU1
AZU1 Gene""" ;
           :definition "This gene plays a role in neutrophil differentiation and is involved in inflammatory processes." ;
           :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C28531" ;
           rdfs:label "AZU1 Gene" .


:Acetaminophen :Synonyms """ACETAMINOPHEN
N-(4-Hydroxyphenyl)acetamide
Acetaminophen
acetaminophen
Paracetamol
4-Hydroxyacetanilide
APAP
Tylenol""" ;
               :definition "A p-aminophenol derivative with analgesic and antipyretic activities. Although the exact mechanism through which acetaminophen exert its effects has yet to be fully determined, acetaminophen may inhibit the nitric oxide (NO) pathway mediated by a variety of neurotransmitter receptors including N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) and substance P, resulting in elevation of the pain threshold. The antipyretic activity may result from inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis and release in the central nervous system (CNS) and prostaglandin-mediated effects on the heat-regulating center in the anterior hypothalamus." ;
               :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C198" ;
               rdfs:label "Acetaminophen" .


:Albendazole :Synonyms """Carbamic Acid,(5-(Propylthio)-1H-benzimidazol-2-yl)-, Methyl Ester
Albendazole
ALBENDAZOLE
Albenza
Bilutac
Proftril
SKF 62979
Zentel""" ;
             :definition "A broad-spectrum, synthetic benzimidazole-derivative anthelmintic. Albendazole interferes with the reproduction and survival of helminths by inhibiting the formation of microtubules from tubulin. This leads to an impaired uptake of glucose, a depletion of glycogen stores, and results in the worm's death. Albendazole is used in the treatment of dog and pork tapeworm-causing diseases, including hydatid disease and neurocysticercosis. Albendazole may also be used to treat a variety of other roundworm infections." ;
             :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C47384" ;
             rdfs:label "Albendazole" .


:Alpha-1-Acid_Glycoprotein_1 :Synonyms """Alpha-1 Acid Glycoprotein
Alpha-1-Acid Glycoprotein
Orosomucoid-1
Alpha-1-Acid Glycoprotein 1
Orosomucoid 1
Epididymis Secretory Sperm Binding Protein Li 153w
AGP 1
OMD 1
ORM1""" ;
                             :definition "Alpha-1-acid glycoprotein 1 (201 aa, ~24 kDa) is encoded by the human ORM1 gene. This protein may play a role in immunosuppression and small molecule transport." ;
                             :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C126967" ;
                             rdfs:label "Alpha-1-Acid Glycoprotein 1" .


:Alpha-1-Antitrypsin :Synonyms """Serpin Peptidase Inhibitor Clade A Member 1
Serine (or Cysteine) Proteinase Inhibitor, Clade A, Member 1
Alpha-1-Antitrypsin
Anti-Elastase
Serpin Family A Member 1
Alpha-1 Antitrypsin
Alpha-1 Protease Inhibitor
Protease Inhibitor 1
Alpha-1-Antiproteinase
Alpha1AT
SERPINA1
Serpin A1""" ;
                     :definition "Alpha-1-antitrypsin (418 aa, ~47 kDa) is encoded by the human SERPINA1 gene. This protein plays a role in regulation of proteolysis." ;
                     :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C105012" ;
                     rdfs:label "Alpha-1-Antitrypsin" .


:Alpha-2-Macroglobulin :Synonyms """Alpha-2-Macroglobulin
C3 and PZP-Like Alpha-2-Macroglobulin Domain-Containing Protein 5
A2M
Alpha-2-M""" ;
                       :definition "Alpha-2-macroglobulin (1474 aa, ~163 kDa) is encoded by the human A2M gene. This protein has activity as a protease inhibitor." ;
                       :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C105924" ;
                       rdfs:label "Alpha-2-Macroglobulin" .


:Amikacin :Synonyms """AMIKACIN
Amikacin
amikacin""" ;
          :definition "A broad-spectrum semi-synthetic aminoglycoside antibiotic, derived from kanamycin with antimicrobial property. Amikacin irreversibly binds to the bacterial 30S ribosomal subunit, specifically locking 16S rRNA and S12 protein within the 30S subunit. This leads to interference with translational initiation complex and misreading of mRNA, thereby hampering protein synthesis and resulting in bactericidal effect. This agent is usually used in short-term treatment of serious infections due to susceptible strains of Gram-negative bacteria." ;
          :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C61615" ;
          rdfs:label "Amikacin" .


:Amiloride :Synonyms """AMILORIDE
Amiloride""" ;
           :definition "A synthetic pyrazine derivative with antikaliuretic and diuretic properties. Amiloride inhibits sodium channels located in the distal tubules and collecting ducts of the kidney, thereby preventing the absorption of sodium and increasing its excretion along with water, to produce naturesis. In response to the hypernatremic conditions in the kidney, the plasma membrane becomes hyperpolarized and electrochemical forces are reduced, which then prevents the excretion of potassium and hydrogen into the lumen." ;
           :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C61633" ;
           rdfs:label "Amiloride" .


:Amorolfine :Synonyms """AMOROLFINE
Amorolfin
Amorolfine
Curanail
Loceryl
Locetar
Odenil""" ;
            :definition "A morpholine antifungal agent for topical use. Amorolfine inhibits delta-14-reductase and delta-7,8-isomerase, which depletes ergosterol and causes ignosterol to accumulate in the fungal cytoplasmic cell membrane." ;
            :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C81332" ;
            rdfs:label "Amorolfine" .


:Amoxicillin :Synonyms """amoxicillin
Amoxicillin Trihydrate
Amoxicillin
AMOXICILLIN
AMOX
Amoxil
Polymox
Trimox
Utimox
Wymox""" ;
             :definition "A broad-spectrum, semisynthetic aminopenicillin antibiotic with bactericidal activity. Amoxicillin binds to and inactivates penicillin-binding protein (PBP) 1A located on the inner membrane of the bacterial cell wall. Inactivation of PBPs interferes with the cross-linkage of peptidoglycan chains necessary for bacterial cell wall strength and rigidity. This interrupts bacterial cell wall synthesis and results in the weakening of the bacterial cell wall and causes cell lysis." ;
             :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C237" ;
             rdfs:label "Amoxicillin" .


:Amphotericin_B :Synonyms """Amphotericin B
amphotericin B
AMPHOTERICIN B
Amphotericin b
AmB
Amphocil
Amphotec""" ;
                :definition "A polyene antifungal antibiotic produced by Streptomyces nodosus, with antifungal activity. Amphotericin B binds to ergosterol, an essential component of the fungal cell membrane, thereby causing depolarization of the membrane and altering cell membrane permeability. This leads to leakage of important intracellular components, cell rupture, and eventually cell death. This agent may also induce oxidative damage in fungal cells and has been reported to stimulate host immune cells." ;
                :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C238" ;
                rdfs:label "Amphotericin B" .


:Ampicillin :Synonyms """(2S,5R,6R)-6-((R)-2-Amino-2-phenylacetamido)-3,3-dimethyl-7-oxo-4-thia-1-azabicyclo(3.2.0)heptane-2-carboxylic Acid
AMPICILLIN
Ampicillin""" ;
            :definition "A broad-spectrum, semi-synthetic, beta-lactam penicillin antibiotic with bactericidal activity. Ampicillin binds to and inactivates penicillin-binding proteins (PBP) located on the inner membrane of the bacterial cell wall. Inactivation of PBPs interferes with the cross-linkage of peptidoglycan chains necessary for bacterial cell wall strength and rigidity. This interrupts bacterial cell wall synthesis and results in the weakening of the bacterial cell wall and causes cell lysis. Ampicillin is stable against hydrolysis by a variety of beta-lactamases, therefore, can be used in wide range of gram-positive and -negative infections." ;
            :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C239" ;
            rdfs:label "Ampicillin" .


:Angiopoietin-1 :Synonyms """Angiopoietin-1
Angiopoietin 1
ANG-1
ANG1
ANGPT1""" ;
                :definition "Angiopoietin-1 (498 aa, ~58 kDa) is encoded by the human ANGPT1 gene. This protein is involved in both signal transduction and angiogenesis." ;
                :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C18042" ;
                rdfs:label "Angiopoietin-1" .


:Angiopoietin-2 :Synonyms """Angiopoietin 2
