:Azithromycin :Synonyms """AZITHROMYCIN, UNSPECIFIED FORM
N-methyl-11-aza-10-deoxy-10-dihydroerythromycin A
Azithromycin
(2R,3S,4R,5R,8R,10R,11R,12S,13S,14R)-13-[(2,6-Dideoxy-3-C-methyl-3-O-methyl-alpha-L-ribo-hexopyranosyl)oxy]-2-ethyl-3,4,10-trihydroxy-3,5,6,8,10,12,14-heptamethyl-11-[(3,4,6-trideoxy-3-(dimethylamino)-beta-D-xylo-hexopyranosyl)oxy]-1-oxa-6-azacyclopentade
AzaSite
CP 62993
XZ-450
Zithromax""" ;
              :definition "An azalide, derived from erythromycin, and a member of a subclass of macrolide antibiotics with bacteriocidal and bacteriostatic activities. Azithromycin reversibly binds to the 50S ribosomal subunit of the 70S ribosome of sensitive microorganisms, thereby inhibiting the translocation step of protein synthesis, wherein a newly synthesized peptidyl tRNA molecule moves from the acceptor site on the ribosome to the peptidyl (donor) site, and consequently inhibiting RNA-dependent protein synthesis leading to cell growth inhibition and cell death." ;
              :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C28844" ;
              rdfs:label "Azithromycin" .


:Aztreonam :Synonyms """AZTREONAM
Azactam
Aztreonam
SQ 26,776""" ;
           :definition "A monocyclic beta-lactam antibiotic originally isolated from Chromobacterium violaceum with bactericidal activity. Aztreonam preferentially binds to and inactivates penicillin-binding protein-3 (PBP-3), which is involved in bacterial cell wall synthesis, thereby inhibiting bacterial cell wall integrity and leading to cell lysis and death. This agent differs from other beta-lactam antibiotics because it is resistant to beta-lactamase hydrolysis, and it is usually used to treat infections caused by gram-negative aerobic microorganisms." ;
           :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C28845" ;
           rdfs:label "Aztreonam" .


