:Methicillin :Synonyms """METHICILLIN
Methicillin""" ;
             :definition "A semisynthetic, narrow spectrum beta-lactamase-resistant penicillin antibiotic with bactericidal and beta-lactamase resistant activity. Methicillin binds to specific penicillin-binding proteins (BPBs) on the bacterial cell wall, thereby preventing the cross-linkage of peptidoglycans, which are critical components of the bacterial cell wall. This leads to an interruption of the bacterial cell wall and causes bacterial lysis." ;
             :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C61842" ;
             rdfs:label "Methicillin" .


:Methylprednisolone :Synonyms """(6alpha,11beta)-11,17,21-Trihydroxy-6-methylpregna-1,4-diene-3,20-dione
Veriderm Medrol
Methylprednisolone
METHYLPREDNISOLONE
Caberdelta M
Depo-Nisolone
Methylprednisolonum
Predni-M-Tablinen
Depo Moderin
6Alpha-Methylprednisolone
DepMedalone
methylprednisolone
Medrol Veriderm
Metilbetasone Solubile
Sieropresol
Adlone
Duralone
Emmetipi
Esametone
Firmacort
Medlone 21
Medrate
Medrol
Medrone
Mega-Star
Meprolone
Metrocort
Metypresol
Metysolon
Prednilen
Radilem
Solpredone
Summicort
Urbason
Wyacort""" ;
                    :definition "A synthetic corticosteroid with anti-inflammatory and immunomodulating properties. Methylprednisolone binds to and activates specific nuclear receptors, resulting in altered gene expression and inhibition of proinflammatory cytokine production. This agent also decreases the number of circulating lymphocytes, induces cell differentiation, and stimulates apoptosis in sensitive tumor cell populations." ;
                    :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C647" ;
                    rdfs:label "Methylprednisolone" .


:Metronidazole :Synonyms """Flagyl I.V. RTU
METRONIDAZOLE
metronidazole
Metronidazole
Flagyl
Tricom""" ;
               :definition "A synthetic nitroimidazole derivative with antiprotozoal and antibacterial activities. Although its mechanism of action is not fully elucidated, un-ionized metronidazole is readily taken up by obligate anaerobic organisms and is subsequently reduced by low-redox potential electron-transport proteins to an active, intermediate product. Reduced metronidazole causes DNA strand breaks, thereby inhibiting DNA synthesis and bacterial cell growth." ;
               :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C651" ;
               rdfs:label "Metronidazole" .


:Miconazole :Synonyms """1-[2-(2,4-Dichlorophenyl)-2-[(2,4-dichlorophenyl)methoxy]ethyl]-1H-imidazole
MICONAZOLE
Miconazole""" ;
            :definition "An antifungal synthetic derivative of imidazole and used in the treatment of candidal skin infections, Miconazole selectively affects the integrity of fungal cell membranes, high in ergosterol content and different in composition from mammalian cells membranes." ;
