:Nitroglycerin :Synonyms """NITROGLYCERIN
Nitroglycerin
nitroglycerin
Rectiv""" ;
               :definition "An organic nitrate with vasodilator activity. Nitroglycerin is converted into nitric oxide (NO) in smooth muscle and activates guanylyl cyclase, thereby increasing cGMP concentration, and resulting in smooth muscle relaxation. Dilatation of the veins results in decreased venous return to the heart, thereby decreasing left ventricular volume (reduced preload) and decreasing myocardial oxygen requirements. Arteriolar relaxation reduces arteriolar resistance (reduced afterload), thereby decreasing myocardial oxygen demands. In addition, nitroglycerine causes coronary artery dilatation, thereby improving myocardial blood distribution." ;
               :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C29294" ;
               rdfs:label "Nitroglycerin" .


:Norfloxacin :Synonyms """1,4-Dihydro-1-ethyl-6-fluoro-4-oxo-7-(1-piperazinyl)-3-quinolinecarboxylic Acid
NORFLOXACIN
Norfloxacin
Baccidal
Fulgram
MK-366
Noroxin
Sebercim""" ;
             :definition "A synthetic, broad-spectrum fluoroquinolone with antibacterial activity. Norfloxacin inhibits activity of DNA gyrase, thereby blocking bacterial DNA replication. Norfloxacin concentrates in the renal tubules and bladder and is bactericidal against a wide range of aerobic gram-positive and gram-negative organisms." ;
             :reference "http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C47638" ;
             rdfs:label "Norfloxacin" .


